---
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import workflowImage from '../../assets/posts/first-post/workflow.png';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="First post on the blog"
  description="Introducing the site, the blog, and the workflow used to publish notebook-driven reports."
>
  <article class="article reveal-in">
    <header class="article-header">
      <p class="article-kicker">2023-02-20 · Alejandro Fontal</p>
      <h1>First post on the blog</h1>
      <p>Introducing the site and the publication workflow behind notebook-based reports.</p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h2>Introduction</h2>
      <p>
        This blog started as a way to document research, programming experiments, and practical workflows for sharing
        technical outputs with both technical and non-technical audiences.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most of my work is still notebook-centric, but the default rendering of notebooks in repository viewers can
        make long analyses difficult to navigate. This motivated the transition toward static sites with stronger
        layout and information architecture.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Static publishing path</h2>
      <p>
        Over time, the stack evolved from Pelican to Jupyter Book and eventually Quarto. The main requirement has
        always been the same: keep source reports close to code while producing polished, searchable outputs.
      </p>
      <p>
        A static pipeline makes this feasible: content lives in notebooks or markdown, the CI build renders HTML, and
        hosting deploys the generated pages.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Current workflow</h2>
      <Image
        src={workflowImage}
        alt="Schematic view of the publication workflow"
        width={1536}
        height={1024}
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <ol>
        <li>Write reports in `.ipynb` or `.qmd` and render locally.</li>
        <li>Push to the main repository branch.</li>
        <li>CI installs dependencies and renders static pages.</li>
        <li>The generated output branch is deployed to hosting.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>
        The blog exists to keep technical notes public, reproducible, and readable. Future posts will continue to
        blend code, scientific context, and communication design.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
